We use nested loops to iterate through all possible pairs of elements from the two arrays. For each pair, we calculate the sum of the absolute differences between elements and their indices. We update the maximum value found so far and return it at the end. This solution has a time complexity of O(n^2) due to the nested loops, where n is the length of the arrays. The space complexity is O(n) because we only use a single integer variable to store the maximum value. The energy implications are low because the calculations involved are simple arithmetic operations and do not consume significant energy.

